<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-334-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 334 816.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mexico's phones to be upgraded with Ericsson deal.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ericsson Inc. (contracts).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsSwitching CentersCommunications EquipmentGovernment ContractsMexico.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MEXICO'S PHONES TO BE UPGRADED WITH ERICCSON DEAL NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A.,andO;1990 APR 5 (NB) -- Ericcson of Sweden, which dominates the market for sellingtelephone switches to the Third World, especially Africa, won an $180 millionswitch contract with the Mexican Telephone Administration, and was expectedto sign further contracts for transmission equipment which could bring thetotal value of the deal to $1.08 billion.andM;In response, the price of Ericcson stock rose sharply on world markets.andP;  Thecompany employs about 4,600 people in Mexico, and exports equipment fromthere to other markets in Latin America.andM;Mexico is in great need of better phone links, but enterprising Mexicans aregetting better service without them.andP;  Newsbytes talked to Ramon Santoyo, aMexico City banker, who noted that it can take two years for businessmen toget a new phone line from the state phone company.andP;  &quot;But you can get acellular line in 2 hours,&quot; he says, with either of the two new cellularservice providers in that country.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900406/Press Contact: Ericsson, Kathy Egan 212/685-4030)</TEXT></DOC>